700
00:52:00,137 --> 00:52:06,137
in a large,
metal barrel
for 110 days.

701
00:52:06,172 --> 00:52:12,068
She and the group of men
would live there confined
and observed around the clock.

702
00:52:14,827 --> 00:52:18,931
Judith Lapierre felt primed
for the challenge.

703
00:52:21,137 --> 00:52:23,931
I'm the woman
taking part in this crew

704
00:52:23,965 --> 00:52:27,344
so we are training now
for the starting
of the experiment.

705
00:52:28,862 --> 00:52:32,310
I would have loved, of course,
there would be more women

706
00:52:32,344 --> 00:52:35,103
because I think
it would be great
for me as support, also,

707
00:52:35,137 --> 00:52:40,137
and real life is
involving both genders,
so there should be more,

708
00:52:40,172 --> 00:52:42,103
but unfortunately,
there's only one so far.

709
00:52:44,827 --> 00:52:51,103
On December 4, 1999,
Judith was ready
to be locked in the barrel

710
00:52:51,137 --> 00:52:56,827
as part of an international
crew that was to join
a Russian crew inside.

711
00:52:58,827 --> 00:53:04,137
I remember following
each other in a line
and going inside the chamber,

712
00:53:04,172 --> 00:53:09,379
closing the doors
and there we were starting
our 110 days' mission.

713
00:53:09,413 --> 00:53:14,241
And it was a very intense
schedule, we had over
100 studies to run.

714
00:53:14,275 --> 00:53:18,206
and the days
would last from 8:00
until 10:00 at night.

715
00:53:21,793 --> 00:53:24,827
Judith settled
into her new life,

716
00:53:24,862 --> 00:53:29,103
comfortably dropping
into a work routine
with her colleagues.

717
00:53:34,896 --> 00:53:40,137
From the control room
the supervisors witnessed
how the crew bonded.

718
00:53:42,344 --> 00:53:48,379
Nobody had the slightest
notion that the experiment
was to go disastrously wrong.

719
00:53:52,379 --> 00:53:55,586
The ambience and the dynamic
of the chamber changed

720
00:53:55,620 --> 00:53:58,379
that evening
of New Year's, 2000.

721
00:53:59,862 --> 00:54:02,620
It was a kind
of a celebration
of course,

722
00:54:02,655 --> 00:54:05,000
we had an initial
meal together

723
00:54:06,586 --> 00:54:12,551
and a little after midnight,
there was a fight
between Russian crew members.

724
00:54:12,586 --> 00:54:15,931
It was a very violent
and aggressive fight

725
00:54:15,965 --> 00:54:18,655
that left one
crew member
very injured.

726
00:54:21,482 --> 00:54:25,206
Judith expected
the men in the control room
to intervene...

727
00:54:27,689 --> 00:54:29,379
but no one came.

728
00:54:33,448 --> 00:54:36,000
This was just one
part of an evening

729
00:54:36,034 --> 00:54:39,551
that was to spiral
much further
out of control.

730
00:54:41,137 --> 00:54:43,689
We couldn't sleep
after those incidents

731
00:54:43,724 --> 00:54:45,310
so we stayed
in the living room.

732
00:54:45,344 --> 00:54:50,586
And then the Russian
crew member
was starting to make jokes

733
00:54:50,620 --> 00:54:54,724
about doing an experiment
that would involve myself.

734
00:54:54,758 --> 00:55:00,758
He had stopped smoking
and he wanted to test
kissing without smoking,

735
00:55:00,793 --> 00:55:04,655
in front of everybody.
So I said, "No way,

736
00:55:04,689 --> 00:55:07,551
I'm not gonna take part
in any of this,
what do you mean?"

737
00:55:07,586 --> 00:55:13,448
And he pulled me up
from my chair.
I sat down again.

738
00:55:13,482 --> 00:55:18,137
He pulled me again
and I looked at my friends,
my commander, saying,

739
00:55:18,172 --> 00:55:20,689
"What's he doing now,
he's pulling me out?"

740
00:55:20,724 --> 00:55:23,206
you know, to go
in the kitchen area again.

741
00:55:23,241 --> 00:55:27,862
That's when he decided
that he would kiss me forcibly

742
00:55:27,896 --> 00:55:31,793
and I pushed him away,
he did again
and I pushed him.

743
00:55:31,827 --> 00:55:36,068
And I left the kitchen,
went back to my colleagues

744
00:55:36,103 --> 00:55:39,068
and I was in shock
because that whole evening

745
00:55:39,103 --> 00:55:42,448
had a whole
atmosphere already
and I couldn't believe it.

746
00:55:53,068 --> 00:55:55,931
The next day we did write
to mission control

747
00:55:55,965 --> 00:55:58,310
and to our respective
space agencies.

748
00:55:58,344 --> 00:56:01,206
And it took
until four
to five days,

749
00:56:01,241 --> 00:56:06,310
they sent to us
a paper through
the hatch doors

750
00:56:06,344 --> 00:56:09,551
and they told us
you should sign this

751
00:56:09,586 --> 00:56:11,551
or you may leave,
you're free to go.

752
00:56:11,586 --> 00:56:16,758
And so we were
kind of forced to sign
if we wanted to stay.

753
00:56:16,793 --> 00:56:18,689
And, of course,
I wanted to stay.

754
00:56:21,620 --> 00:56:23,620
The paper
Judith signed

755
00:56:23,655 --> 00:56:28,103
said that the incident
was just a cultural
misunderstanding.

756
00:56:29,896 --> 00:56:35,620
And I can't say no to that.
It was a sexual interest
that he had in me

757
00:56:35,655 --> 00:56:39,793
and he forcibly
kissed me twice
and I rejected him.

758
00:56:39,827 --> 00:56:42,551
But it was not
recognized as such

759
00:56:42,586 --> 00:56:46,827
and it was just minimized as
a cultural misunderstanding.

760
00:56:46,862 --> 00:56:51,068
Saying that I wasn't
open enough to
cultural diversity.

761
00:56:58,620 --> 00:57:00,137
When that mission finished,

762
00:57:01,413 --> 00:57:03,758
it really influenced
my whole career,

763
00:57:03,793 --> 00:57:07,586
because I thought
this would be the start
of my research project

764
00:57:07,620 --> 00:57:11,655
with the Space Agency
or the start of my field
of work.

765
00:57:11,689 --> 00:57:15,724
But I was just totally
pushed out of the system.

766
00:57:15,758 --> 00:57:20,137
And I have not been involved
in any space work ever since.

767
00:57:34,655 --> 00:57:38,241
Drawing on
the experience
of Judith Lapierre,

768
00:57:38,275 --> 00:57:41,965
one concludes that hurtling
through the centuries

769
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:47,241
in a spaceship,
would end in strife,
crime and depravity.

770
00:57:54,896 --> 00:57:59,034
If we are to stand a chance
to reach exoplanets,

771
00:57:59,068 --> 00:58:02,965
we need to figure out how
to get there in a lifetime.

772
00:58:04,965 --> 00:58:08,517
But could we invent
a spacecraft fast enough?

773
00:58:17,034 --> 00:58:20,620
In Idaho, we are back
with Marshall Savage,

774
00:58:20,655 --> 00:58:24,689
visionary science educator
and futurologist.

775
00:58:26,310 --> 00:58:31,724
Marshall has an idea
how we can supercharge
future spacecraft.

776
00:58:34,793 --> 00:58:39,000
Einstein taught us
energy and matter
are inter-exchangeable,

777
00:58:39,034 --> 00:58:42,551
and a very little bit
of matter is a huge amount
of energy.

778
00:58:42,586 --> 00:58:46,586
But the only real,
viable way to make
that conversion,

779
00:58:46,620 --> 00:58:49,206
to get all the energy
out of a piece of matter,

780
00:58:49,241 --> 00:58:50,689
is by having antimatter.

781
00:58:50,724 --> 00:58:53,379
Because when matter
and antimatter meet,

782
00:58:53,413 --> 00:58:56,793
they annihilate each other
and the result is pure energy.

783
00:58:58,931 --> 00:59:03,448
So, if you could manufacture
and store enough antimatter,

784
00:59:03,482 --> 00:59:08,137
it then becomes possible
to have energy on the scale
of photon propulsion.

785
00:59:08,172 --> 00:59:12,103
What that means is that
instead of hot chemicals
coming out of the rocket,

786
00:59:12,137 --> 00:59:15,413
or fast fusion particles
coming out of the rocket,

787
00:59:15,448 --> 00:59:17,862
you have photons
coming out of the rocket,

788
00:59:17,896 --> 00:59:19,275
and they're traveling
at the speed of light.

789
00:59:29,551 --> 00:59:34,034
Antimatter fuel
would get us around
the galaxy in no time.

790
00:59:40,931 --> 00:59:43,551
As impossible as it may sound,

791
00:59:43,586 --> 00:59:49,862
antimatter is both
already manufactured
and stored on Earth today.

792
00:59:49,896 --> 00:59:55,241
In Geneva,
physicist Michael Doser
harvests antimatter

793
00:59:55,275 --> 00:59:57,896
at the particle
accelerator, CERN.

794
00:59:59,655 --> 01:00:03,689
It's actually pretty easy
to make antimatter
and to work with it.

795
01:00:03,724 --> 01:00:06,413
All you need is
a Proton Synchrotron,

796
01:00:06,448 --> 01:00:09,551
where you accelerate particles
to very high energies,

797
01:00:09,586 --> 01:00:12,413
smash those into
a block of iridium,

798
01:00:12,448 --> 01:00:15,000
and if you're really lucky,
one in a million,

799
01:00:15,034 --> 01:00:17,551
you get a pair
of a proton
and antiproton.

800
01:00:17,586 --> 01:00:21,241
These antiprotons are moving
almost at the speed of light,

801
01:00:21,275 --> 01:00:22,689
rush into this building,

802
01:00:22,724 --> 01:00:25,758
and are then slowed down
in the structures
that you can see here.

803
01:00:25,793 --> 01:00:29,896
So, there's a big
decelerator surrounding
the building itself,

804
01:00:29,931 --> 01:00:31,448
underneath
the concrete blocks.

805
01:00:31,482 --> 01:00:35,000
Then they go down into
this little ring here,

806
01:00:35,034 --> 01:00:36,482
which is the final stage,

807
01:00:36,517 --> 01:00:39,827
which slows them down
to such low energies
that we can catch them.

808
01:00:44,827 --> 01:00:49,275
Making antimatter
is easy, if you happen
to be at CERN,

809
01:00:49,310 --> 01:00:53,206
the world's largest
nuclear research facility.

810
01:00:53,241 --> 01:00:58,068
The center hosts scientists
from 85 nations

811
01:00:58,103 --> 01:01:03,482
and consumes more electricity
than 300,000 homes a year.

812
01:01:11,137 --> 01:01:16,000
CERN might be the home
of some of the biggest
hardware ever built,

813
01:01:16,034 --> 01:01:20,689
but in particle physics
some of the most
impressive gear

814
01:01:20,724 --> 01:01:22,275
can be quite unassuming.

815
01:01:24,551 --> 01:01:28,034
This is the heart
of the matter,
or of the antimatter.

816
01:01:28,068 --> 01:01:30,206
This is what an antimatter
trap looks like,

817
01:01:30,241 --> 01:01:34,172
and this is, in fact,
a trap that we used about
10,15 years ago.

818
01:01:34,206 --> 01:01:36,379
And what you see here is

819
01:01:36,413 --> 01:01:39,413
something that will hold
antimatter without touching
any matter.

820
01:01:39,448 --> 01:01:42,655
Because, of course, when
antimatter and matter touch,
they annihilate.

821
01:01:42,689 --> 01:01:45,172
So we need to hold
the antimatter in vacuum,

822
01:01:45,206 --> 01:01:48,655
and only touch it
with electric fields
and magnetic fields.

823
01:01:52,275 --> 01:01:56,310
Unfortunately,
the amount of energy required

824
01:01:56,344 --> 01:01:59,931
to make antimatter
is enormous.

825
01:01:59,965 --> 01:02:06,000
120 gigawatts are
needed to create even
the tiniest amounts

826
01:02:06,034 --> 01:02:08,310
of this mysterious substance.

827
01:02:09,172 --> 01:02:11,758
And the output
is ridiculously low.

828
01:02:13,965 --> 01:02:17,034
All the antimatter
produced at CERN

829
01:02:17,068 --> 01:02:19,482
wouldn't power
a single lightbulb.

830
01:02:23,896 --> 01:02:29,103
Michael Doser works
with only minute quantities
of antimatter.

831
01:02:31,344 --> 01:02:33,965
And there is another problem.

832
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:38,344
The sheer amount
of time required to
manufacture antimatter.

833
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:45,724
At CERN, if the accelerator
were to give us antiprotons
every second,

834
01:02:45,758 --> 01:02:47,379
and we could cool them
down that fast,

835
01:02:47,413 --> 01:02:52,103
we'd end up with something
of the order of a tenth
of a nanogram per year.

836
01:02:52,137 --> 01:02:56,517
Which means, that in order
to get one gram of antimatter
you need 10 billion years,

837
01:02:56,551 --> 01:02:58,896
which just happens to be
the age of the universe.

838
01:02:58,931 --> 01:03:02,551
So if you'd started collecting
antiprotons at the beginning
of the universe,

839
01:03:02,586 --> 01:03:03,862
at the moment of the big bang,

840
01:03:03,896 --> 01:03:05,793
we'd now have 1 gram
of antimatter.

841
01:03:08,448 --> 01:03:12,724
Even if this lengthy
production process
were practical,

842
01:03:12,758 --> 01:03:19,310
could we ever generate
enough fuel to get us
to the next solar system?

843
01:03:19,344 --> 01:03:24,586
Now, to get to Alpha Centauri,
my reference is Star Trek,
which has the Enterprise.

844
01:03:24,620 --> 01:03:28,206
And in the Enterprise
there's this huge warp core
running with antimatter.

845
01:03:28,241 --> 01:03:30,655
That's a couple of tons'
worth of antimatter,

846
01:03:30,689 --> 01:03:34,896
but we can be a bit more
economical than that,
and call it a few kilograms.

847
01:03:34,931 --> 01:03:38,344
Which means that,
not only do you need
10 billion years,

848
01:03:38,379 --> 01:03:42,344
you actually need something
like a factor of 1,000
or 10,000 more than that,

849
01:03:42,379 --> 01:03:46,379
which is probably longer
than the age of the universe
into the future.

850
01:03:46,413 --> 01:03:49,931
And that's the amount of time
you need, under current
technological conditions

851
01:03:49,965 --> 01:03:52,517
to make enough antimatter
to get to Alpha Centauri.

852
01:03:52,551 --> 01:03:54,620
You'd be faster off
walking to get there.

853
01:04:15,655 --> 01:04:19,000
For now,
interstellar space travel

854
01:04:19,034 --> 01:04:21,862
remains in the realm
of science fiction.

855
01:04:28,034 --> 01:04:32,000
Unless, of course,
we get help from
outer space.

856
01:04:34,827 --> 01:04:38,206
If there were
technically-advanced
aliens out there,

857
01:04:38,241 --> 01:04:41,275
we could just ask them
to let us hitch a ride.

858
01:04:56,241 --> 01:05:00,068
Those of us
hoping to get a lift
from a UFO

859
01:05:00,103 --> 01:05:07,448
should best direct
their request to this colony
of extraterrestrials on Earth.

860
01:05:07,482 --> 01:05:11,551
In the Valley of the Dawn,
in Brazil, live people who
believe they are

861
01:05:11,586 --> 01:05:16,517
the descendants
of an alien species
from the planet Capella.

862
01:06:04,965 --> 01:06:09,103
The knowledge about
the extraterrestrial
history of the valley

863
01:06:09,137 --> 01:06:12,241
goes back to this woman,
Tia Neiva.

864
01:06:15,275 --> 01:06:22,172
Born Neiva Zelaya,
Tia Neiva was a truck driver
and single mother of four.

865
01:06:22,206 --> 01:06:28,620
When she died in 1984,
her followers preserved
her house as she had left it.

866
01:06:31,758 --> 01:06:34,931
They even turned her bathroom
into a shrine.

867
01:06:38,620 --> 01:06:43,448
Photographs show how from
the 1960s onwards,

868
01:06:43,482 --> 01:06:46,034
she started receiving
cosmic energy.

869
01:06:50,275 --> 01:06:53,758
The energy is sent down
from the alien mothership

870
01:06:53,793 --> 01:06:56,655
that hovers invisibly
above the valley.

871
01:07:23,551 --> 01:07:29,413
Tia Neiva's followers
are still harvesting
healing rays today

872
01:07:29,448 --> 01:07:32,413
transmitted down
by benevolent aliens.

873
01:07:34,517 --> 01:07:39,551
So could this energy
be used to whisk us away
to faraway planets?

874
01:08:24,103 --> 01:08:27,551
The aliens
of the valley
are stuck on Earth.

875
01:08:27,586 --> 01:08:33,275
In the course of millennia,
their bodies have adapted
to our environment,

876
01:08:33,310 --> 01:08:36,103
so there's no way back
to their home planet.

877
01:08:43,379 --> 01:08:46,758
Watching them draw
energy from outer space,

878
01:08:46,793 --> 01:08:49,655
we were mystified
by the experience.

879
01:08:49,689 --> 01:08:55,068
Which seemed at times
as perplexing as gazing
at a faraway galaxy.

880
01:09:22,310 --> 01:09:25,620
We left the aliens
of the Valley of Dawn

881
01:09:25,655 --> 01:09:28,655
with a certainty
that they would not be able

882
01:09:28,689 --> 01:09:31,241
to whisk us away
in their spacecraft.

883
01:09:36,206 --> 01:09:38,586
Our journey has shown us

884
01:09:38,620 --> 01:09:42,724
that we humans
should not behave
like interplanetary locusts

885
01:09:43,344 --> 01:09:45,689
grazing our planet empty

886
01:09:45,724 --> 01:09:47,965
and then moving onto the next.

887
01:09:50,655 --> 01:09:52,758
But should we be sad
about that?

888
01:10:01,965 --> 01:10:04,448
Since his journeys
to the stars,

889
01:10:04,482 --> 01:10:08,448
astronaut Mike Foale looks
at our planet differently.

890
01:10:11,206 --> 01:10:14,137
I've always loved astronomy.
I've always loved the galaxy.

891
01:10:14,172 --> 01:10:17,517
I've always loved the idea
of being on other planets
around other stars.

892
01:10:20,517 --> 01:10:24,000
But in the end
the thing that drove me
the most was looking at Earth.

893
01:10:34,586 --> 01:10:38,172
The Earth is always changing
and so the light changes,

894
01:10:38,206 --> 01:10:41,448
the seasons change,
the seasons
are always different.

895
01:10:41,482 --> 01:10:44,482
And it's so fascinating,
it's utterly absorbing.

896
01:10:47,827 --> 01:10:50,896
Coming over the southern tip
of South America,
and almost always,

897
01:10:50,931 --> 01:10:52,827
the lighting
is pretty low-angle.

898
01:10:52,862 --> 01:10:54,965
So it has a sort of
deep dark blue.

899
01:10:55,620 --> 01:10:56,655
Almost a mysterious...

900
01:10:56,689 --> 01:10:58,344
It looks cold, it is cold.

901
01:10:59,103 --> 01:11:00,103
But then you notice...

902
01:11:00,793 --> 01:11:01,931
I could see waves.

903
01:11:02,655 --> 01:11:05,000
And you go, "Waves?

904
01:11:05,034 --> 01:11:07,620
From this altitude?
No, no, that can't be right."

905
01:11:07,655 --> 01:11:12,655
Yes, you can see waves,
South Atlantic waves

906
01:11:12,689 --> 01:11:17,137
going all the way
around the planet
at that latitude.

907
01:11:17,172 --> 01:11:20,103
Because they're
so huge driven by
the winds down there,

908
01:11:20,137 --> 01:11:24,172
you can actually see
the combined froth of
all the breaking waves

909
01:11:24,206 --> 01:11:27,275
from space, from orbit,
from hundreds of miles away.

910
01:11:32,551 --> 01:11:36,172
I appreciate the Earth,
and the ecology of the Earth.

911
01:11:36,206 --> 01:11:40,896
And as something I need
to communicate as being
worthwhile looking after,

912
01:11:40,931 --> 01:11:42,586
far more after being in space.

913
01:11:54,068 --> 01:11:56,758
Back at
Mauna Kea, Hawaii,

914
01:11:56,793 --> 01:12:00,034
the telescopes are trained
into the skies

915
01:12:00,068 --> 01:12:04,931
searching for undiscovered
worlds that might one day
be colonized.

916
01:12:09,655 --> 01:12:14,931
Down on the plains,
native Hawaiians have
a very different idea

917
01:12:14,965 --> 01:12:18,379
of what humanity's place
in the cosmos should be.

918
01:12:28,137 --> 01:12:31,172
This is
a highly symbolic place.

919
01:12:31,206 --> 01:12:35,551
In this black wasteland
Nobel Prize-winning science

920
01:12:35,586 --> 01:12:37,931
collides with
indigenous knowledge.

921
01:12:43,793 --> 01:12:49,655
Hawaiian activist
Lanakila Mangauil
pays reverence to the volcano.

922
01:12:51,827 --> 01:12:55,172
For him, Mauna Kea
is a holy mountain

